a Voz: The "Difference" of Moyeneí Valdés's Sound Break Politics -- tPart III. MIGRATIONS/DISRUPTING (B)ORDERS -- tChapter Eleven. Translation and Transnationalization of Domestic Service -- tChapter Twelve. Chilean Domestic Labor: A Feminist Silence -- tChapter Thirteen. Performing Seduction and National Identity: Brazilian Erotic Dancers in New York -- tChapter Fourteen. Transnational Sex Travels: Negotiating Identities in a Brazilian "Tropical Paradise" -- tPart IV. MOVEMENTS/FEMINIST/SOCIAL/POLITICAL/POSTCOLONIAL -- tChapter Fifteen. Translenguas: Mapping the Possibilities and Challenges of Transnational Women's Organizing across Geographies of Difference -- tChapter Sixteen. Queer/Lesbiana Dialogues among Feminist Movements in the Américas -- tChapter Seventeen. Learning from Latinas: Translating Our Bodies, Ourselves as Transnational Feminist Text -- tChapter Eighteen. Women with Guns: Translating Gender in I, Rigoberta Menchú -- tChapter Nineteen. Translocal Space of Afro-Latinidad: Critical Feminist Visions for Diasporic Bridge-Building -- tChapter Twenty. Translations and Refusals: Resignifying Meanings as Feminist Political Practice -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTranslocalities/Translocalidades is a path-breaking collection of essays on Latin American, Caribbean, and United States-based Latina feminisms and their multiple translations and cross-pollinations. The contributors come from countries throughout the Américas and are based in diverse disciplines, including media studies, literature, Chicana/o studies, and political science. Together, they advocate a hemispheric politics based on the knowledge that today, many sorts of Latin/o-americanidades-Afro, queer, indigenous, feminist, and so on-are constructed through processes of translocation. Latinidad in the South, North and Caribbean "middle" of the Américas, is constituted out of the intersections of the intensified cross-border, transcultural, and translocal flows that characterize contemporary transmigration throughout the hemisphere, from La Paz to Buenos Aires to Chicago and back again. Rather than immigrating and assimilating, many people in the Latin/a Américas increasingly move back and forth between localities, between historically situated and culturally specific, though increasingly porous, places, across multiple borders, and not just between nations. The contributors deem these multidirectional crossings and movements, and the positionalities engendered, translocalities/translocalidades.Contributors. Sonia E. Alvarez, Kiran Asher, Victoria (Vicky) M. Bañales, Marisa Belausteguigoitia Rius, Maylei Blackwell, Cruz C. Bueno, Pascha Bueno-Hansen, Mirangela Buggs, Teresa Carrillo, Claudia de Lima Costa, Isabel Espinal, Verónica Feliu, Macarena Gómez-Barris, Rebecca J. Hester, Norma Klahn, Agustín Lao-Montes, Suzana Maia, Márgara Millán, Adriana Piscitelli, Ana Rebeca Prada, Ester R. Shapiro, Simone Pereira Schmidt, Millie Thayer  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aLao-Montes, Agustín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlvarez, Sonia E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrada, Ana Rebeca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosta, Claudia De Lima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosta, Claudia de Lima, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShapiro, Ester R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeliu, Veronica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHester, Rebecca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/